### Lean 4 Proof with `have` Statements

```lean
lemma offDiagonalHasLaw (n : ℕ) {i j : Fin n} (h : i ≠ j) :
    HasLaw (fun ω ↦ (wignerMatrixMap n ω) i j) μ (WignerMeasure μ ν n) := by
  have h₁ : i < j ∨ j < i := by sorry
  have h₂ : HasLaw (fun ω ↦ (wignerMatrixMap n ω) i j) μ (WignerMeasure μ ν n) := by sorry
  sorry
```

### Explanation of `have` Statements

1. **First `have h₁`**: We start by noting that for any two distinct indices `i` and `j`, either `i < j` or `j < i`. This follows from the fact that `Fin n` is a totally ordered set. 

2. **Second `have h₂`**: This directly states the conclusion that the entry `(i, j)` of the Wigner matrix has law `μ`. The actual proof of this statement will depend on whether `i < j` or `j < i`, as the Wigner matrix is symmetric and we need to use the appropriate case of the independent entries in the Wigner space. 

Both `have` statements are marked with `sorry`, as this is just a sketch of the proof structure. However, the second `have` can either be obtained by case distinction using `h₁` or by observing that the `i ≠ j` case can be reduced to `i < j` using the symmetry of the Wigner matrix.

### Complete Lean 4 Proof

```lean
lemma offDiagonalHasLaw (n : ℕ) {i j : Fin n} (h : i ≠ j) :
    HasLaw (fun ω ↦ (wignerMatrixMap n ω) i j) μ (WignerMeasure μ ν n) := by
  have h₁ : i < j ∨ j < i := by
    cases' lt_or_gt_of_ne h with h₂ h₂
    · exact Or.inl h₂
    · exact Or.inr h₂
  
  have h₂ : HasLaw (fun ω ↦ (wignerMatrixMap n ω) i j) μ (WignerMeasure μ ν n) := by
    -- Use the fact that either i < j or j < i to prove the has law property
    cases h₁ with
    | inl h₁ =>
      -- Case: i < j
      -- Use the offDiagonalHasLaw' lemma to get the result directly
      exact offDiagonalHasLaw' n i j ⟨h₁⟩
    | inr h₁ =>
      -- Case: j < i
      -- Use the symmetry of the Wigner matrix to reduce to the i < j case
      have h₃ : HasLaw (fun ω => (wignerMatrixMap n ω) j i) μ (WignerMeasure μ ν n) := offDiagonalHasLaw' n j i ⟨h₁⟩
      have h₄ : (fun ω => (wignerMatrixMap n ω) i j) = (fun ω => (wignerMatrixMap n ω) j i) := by
        funext ω
        rw [show (wignerMatrixMap n ω) i j = (wignerMatrixMap n ω) j i by
          -- Use the symmetry property of the Wigner matrix
          have h₅ := wignerMatrixSymmetric n i j ω
          simp [h₅]
        ]
      rw [h₄]
      exact h₃
  
  exact h₂
```
